1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,860
Once we have tokenized text,

2

00:00:01,860  -->  00:00:05,900
we can start building machine learning models using it.

3

00:00:05,900  -->  00:00:11,500
In this video, we will talk about one of the simplest models we can build.

4

00:00:11,500  -->  00:00:16,780
We will start with simpler models to learn about their downsides,

5

00:00:16,780  -->  00:00:23,600
which will help us to better understand the advantages of more sophisticated models.

6

00:00:23,600  -->  00:00:28,070
In this video, we will start with the bag-of-words model.

7

00:00:28,070  -->  00:00:31,470
The way it works, it receives a binary vector

8

00:00:31,470  -->  00:00:35,710
as an input where every value is one or zero,

9

00:00:35,710  -->  00:00:40,690
and we create this binary vector from input token IDs.

10

00:00:40,690  -->  00:00:42,610
Let's see how it works.

11

00:00:42,610  -->  00:00:45,010
To use the bag-of-words model,

12

00:00:45,010  -->  00:00:50,550
we start with an input sentence and split it into individual tokens.

13

00:00:50,550  -->  00:00:54,655
We then convert all words to lower case,

14

00:00:54,655  -->  00:00:59,790
and remove tokens for words that have very little useful information,

15

00:00:59,790  -->  00:01:01,310
such as a,

16

00:01:01,310  -->  00:01:02,730
the, and so on.

17

00:01:02,730  -->  00:01:05,965
These are also called stop words.

18

00:01:05,965  -->  00:01:10,650
We then convert each token into a corresponding token ID.

19

00:01:10,650  -->  00:01:13,050
Once we have these IDs,

20

00:01:13,050  -->  00:01:15,950
we convert them into an input vector.

21

00:01:15,950  -->  00:01:21,910
The way we do this is that if we have a token ID with values 345,

22

00:01:21,910  -->  00:01:25,380
we set one in the corresponding position,

23

00:01:25,380  -->  00:01:29,400
and we do the same for all other input IDs.

24

00:01:29,400  -->  00:01:36,560
This input vector will have as many elements as we have unique words in our vocabulary.

25

00:01:36,560  -->  00:01:41,860
If we've decided that our vocabulary will have 65,000 words,

26

00:01:41,860  -->  00:01:46,195
our input vector will have this number of elements.

27

00:01:46,195  -->  00:01:49,310
Now, having a binary vector,

28

00:01:49,310  -->  00:01:56,590
we can pass this input to a neural network or use some other machine learning models.

29

00:01:56,590  -->  00:02:00,150
If we train the model based on these input vectors,

30

00:02:00,150  -->  00:02:03,230
our model can learn to classify text.

31

00:02:03,230  -->  00:02:09,870
For example, by classifying messages into SPAM or non-SPAM messages.

32

00:02:09,870  -->  00:02:14,780
Bag-of-words model is one of the simplest models we could build.

33

00:02:14,780  -->  00:02:16,990
It can work in some cases,

34

00:02:16,990  -->  00:02:19,390
but it has a lot of drawbacks.

35

00:02:19,390  -->  00:02:22,170
First of all, it ignores the words order,

36

00:02:22,170  -->  00:02:26,450
which you might imagine is important for understanding language.

37

00:02:26,450  -->  00:02:29,900
It also ignores grammatical structure of sentences,

38

00:02:29,900  -->  00:02:32,175
like it ignores punctuation.

39

00:02:32,175  -->  00:02:36,040
The other issue is that each token representation that

40

00:02:36,040  -->  00:02:39,940
the model uses has very limited semantic meaning.

41

00:02:39,940  -->  00:02:46,060
For each token, it just records if a word was present in the input text.

42

00:02:46,060  -->  00:02:50,040
The final issue we will talk about is that the model

43

00:02:50,040  -->  00:02:54,980
can't handle words if we didn't see them during training.

44

00:02:54,980  -->  00:02:59,940
While this model can work reasonably well on some simple tasks,

45

00:02:59,940  -->  00:03:04,220
in most cases, we need to use more sophisticated models.

46

00:03:04,220  -->  00:03:09,180
Now we will talk about two improvement for this simple approach.

47

00:03:09,180  -->  00:03:14,600
First of all, we will talk about a better way to represent words, and second,

48

00:03:14,600  -->  00:03:20,720
we will talk about more advanced neural network architectures for NLP tasks.
